{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14703"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.06,0.06,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58078"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7396"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2491"},{"type":"tags","id":"2831"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58078"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive exertional dyspnoea and fatigue. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked and has no history of recreational drug use. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a loud P2 and a right ventricular heave. Chest X-ray shows prominent pulmonary arteries. Echocardiogram demonstrates right ventricular enlargement with normal left ventricular function. CTPA done looking for PE was negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERight heart catheterization reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Mean pulmonary arterial pressure: 45 mmHg (10-20)\u003Cbr /\u003E- Pulmonary capillary wedge pressure: 8 mmHg (6-12)\u003Cbr /\u003E- Pulmonary vascular resistance: 8 Wood units (\u0026lt;3)\u003Cbr /\u003E- Cardiac output: 4.2 L/min (4-8)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary pulmonary hypertension","Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension","Pulmonary venoocclusive disease","Left heart failure","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of pulmonary hypertension, confirmed by right heart catheterization showing elevated mean pulmonary arterial pressure with normal pulmonary capillary wedge pressure. The absence of underlying conditions and the haemodynamic profile is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary pulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E, now termed pulmonary arterial hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with an elevated pulmonary capillary wedge pressure (\u0026gt;15 mmHg) reflecting elevated left atrial pressure. This patient\u0027s wedge pressure is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E would typically have a history of previous deep vein thrombosis or pulmonary embolism, and characteristic findings on CT pulmonary angiogram, which are not mentioned here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary venoocclusive disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of pulmonary hypertension that typically presents with more severe hypoxemia and characteristic changes on chest imaging including interstitial oedema and pleural effusions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E causing pulmonary hypertension would typically show characteristic changes on chest imaging including hilar lymphadenopathy and interstitial changes, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of primary pulmonary hypertension is supported by the young age, female predominance, absence of other causes, and the haemodynamic profile showing pre-capillary pulmonary hypertension (elevated mean pulmonary arterial pressure with normal wedge pressure).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary pulmonary hypertension is characterized by elevated pulmonary arterial pressures with normal pulmonary capillary wedge pressure.","Right heart catheterization is the gold standard for diagnosing pulmonary hypertension.","Mean pulmonary arterial pressure \u003E20 mmHg is diagnostic of pulmonary hypertension."],"references":["2022 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43538"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T20:54:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T20:54:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7396"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58078"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47